Likelihood-free inference¶


For many models in biology (e.g. stochastic / agent-based models) we cannot either write down or compute the likelihood.


So we need a way to make progress - one way to do this is to use repeated simulation of the model.


To keep things simple in this mini-tutorial, we will use the same model, and "pretend" that we cannot evaluate the likelihood.
\begin{equation*} \dfrac{\textrm{d}T(t)}{\textrm{d}t}=-k\left(T(t) - T_a\right) \quad\Longrightarrow\quad T(t)=\left(T(0)-T_{a}\right)\textrm{e}^{-kt}+T_{a}. \end{equation*}

# plot the model solution and the data
display(p1);

Approximate Bayesian computation (ABC)¶


We will use an ABC rejection sampler to compute an approximate posterior, $\mathbb{P}_\text{ABC}(\theta\,|\,T^o(t))$.


Repeat the following steps a very large number of times:

  1. Sample a parameter $\theta$ from the prior distribution.
  2. Simulation the model using theta to give data $T^\text{sim}(t;\theta)$.
  3. Accept the parameter sample $\theta$ into the posterior distribution if \begin{equation*} d(T^\text{sim}(t;\theta),T^o(t))<\epsilon. \end{equation*}


Here $\epsilon>0$ is the acceptance threshold, and the distance function, $d$, is given by \begin{equation*} d(T^\text{sim}(t;\theta),T^o(t))=\sum_{i=1}^I\left(T^\text{sim}(t_i;\theta)-T^o(t_i)\right)^2. \end{equation*}

Convergence of ABC rejection sampler¶


As $\epsilon\to0$, the ABC posterior converges to the true posterior: \begin{equation*} \mathbb{P}_\text{ABC}(\theta\,|\,T^o(t))\to\mathbb{P}(\theta\,|\,T^o(t)). \end{equation*}


It's important to be aware that the ABC posterior will change as $\epsilon$ is varied!
